* RESPONSE 1 *
**************
To solve the question "What building is opposite the ceremonial meeting place of the Accession Council in the United Kingdom?", we first identify the meeting place of the Accession Council. The Accession Council is the body that meets to proclaim a new monarch in the United Kingdom. Historically and traditionally, this council meets at St James's Palace in London.

Specifically, the meeting takes place in the Picture Gallery or the Entrée Room within St James's Palace. The most ceremonial part of the event is the reading of the Proclamation, which occurs from the balcony of Friary Court (the Proclamation Gallery) on the eastern side of the palace.

Friary Court overlooks Marlborough Road. Directly opposite Friary Court, across Marlborough Road, is Marlborough House (which currently serves as the headquarters of the Commonwealth Secretariat). While the Queen's Chapel is also located across from Friary Court, Marlborough House is the more prominent building and is the one most commonly cited as being opposite the ceremonial meeting place of the Accession Council.

Finish[Marlborough House]
